SIMPLE: picturesque
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Picturesque
<hw>Pic`tur*esque"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[It.
<ets>pittoresco</ets>: cf. F. <ets>pittoresque</ets>. See
<er>Pictorial</er>.]</ety> <def>Forming, or fitted to form, a good or
pleasing picture; representing with the clearness or ideal beauty
appropriate to a picture; expressing that peculiar kind of beauty which
is agreeable in a picture, natural or artificial; graphic; vivid;
<as>as, a <ex>picturesque</ex> scene or attitude; <ex>picturesque</ex>
language.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What is <qex>picturesque</qex> as placed in relation to the
beautiful and the sublime? It is . . . the characteristic pushed into a
sensible excess.</q> <au>De Quincey.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Pic`tur*esque"ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Pic`tur*esque"ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Picturesquish</ent>⟦br⟧
